Hardcore punk often abbreviated hardcore punk rock music genre and subculture that originated the late 1970s generally faster harder and more aggressive than other forms punk rock Its roots can traced earlier punk scenes San Francisco and Southern California which arose reaction against the still predominant hippie cultural climate the time was also inspired New York punk rock and early protopunk New York punk had harderedged sound than its San Francisco counterpart featuring antiart expressions masculine anger energy and subversive humor Hardcore punk generally disavows commercialism the established music industry and anything similar the characteristics mainstream rock and often addresses social and political topics with confrontational politicallycharged lyrics Hardcore sprouted underground scenes across the United States the early 1980s particularly Washington New York New Jersey and Bostonas well Australia Canada and the United Kingdom Hardcore has spawned the straight edge movement and its associated submovements hardline and youth crew Hardcore was heavily involved the rise the independent record labels the 1980s and with the DIY ethics underground music scenes has also influenced various music genres that have experienced widespread commercial success including alternative rock and thrash metal While traditional hardcore has never experienced mainstream commercial success some its early pioneers have garnered appreciation over time Black Flags Damaged Minutemens Double Nickels the Dime and Hsker New Day Rising were included Rolling Stones list The 500 Greatest Albums All Time 2003 and Dead Kennedys have seen one their albums reach gold status over period years 2011 Rolling Stone writer David Fricke placed Greg Ginn Black Flag 99th place his 100 Greatest Guitarists list Although the music genre started Englishspeaking western countries notable hardcore scenes have existed Italy Brazil Japan Europe and the Middle East Steven Blush states that the Vancouverbased band DOAs 1981 album Hardcore was where the genre got its name This album also helped make people aware the term hardcore Konstantin Butz states that while the origin the expression hardcore cannot ascribed specific place time the term usually associated with the further evolution Californias Punk Rock scene which included young skateboarders September 1981 article Tim Sommer shows the author applying the term the punk bands gigging around the city that time which considered belated development relative Los Angeles San Francisco and Washington Hardcore historian Steven Blush said that the term hardcore also reference the sense being fed with the existing punk and new wave music Blush also states that the term refers extreme the absolute most Punk Kelefa Sanneh states that the term hardcore referred attitude turning inwards towards the scene and ignoring broader society all with the goal achieving sense shared purpose and being part community Sanneh cites Agnostic Fronts band member selection approach example hardcores emphasis scene citizenship prospective members the band were chosen based being part the local hardcore scene and being regularly the moshing pit shows rather than based musical audition article Drowned Sound argues that 1980sera hardcore the true spirit punk because after all the poseurs and fashionistas fucked off the next trend skinny pink ties with New Romantic haircuts singing wimpy lyrics the punk scene consisted only people completely dedicated the DIY ethics One definition the genre form exceptionally harsh punk rock Like the subgenre the hardcore punk can considered internal music reaction Hardcore has been called faster meaner genre punk that was also stern refutation punk rock rebellion against rebellion Steven Blush states that even though punk rock had unruly edge Reaganera kids demanded something even more primal and immediate with speed and aggression the starting point According one writer distressed the artificiality sic much postpunk and the emasculated sellouts new wave hardcore sought strengthen its core punk principles Lacking the artschool grace postpunk hardcore punk favored low key visual aesthetic over extravagance and breaking with original punk rock song patterns Hardcore disavowssynthetic technological effectsand the recording industry Around 1980 punk became moribund and radiofriendly angry shornheaded suburban teenagers discarded new waves artistic statements and pop music influences and created new genre hardcore for which there were places play which forced the performers create independent and DIY venues Music writer Barney Hoskyns compared punk rock with hardcore and stated that hardcore was younger faster and angrier full the pent rage dysfunctional Orange County Los Angeles adolescents who were sick their life bland Republican area While the hardcore scene was mostly young white males both onstage and the audience there are notable exceptions such the allAfricanAmerican band Bad Brains and notable women such Crass singer Joy Vivre and Black Flags second bassist Kira Roessler Steven Blush states that Minor Threats Ian MacKaye set motion diehard mindset that begat almost everything now call Hardcore with his virulent antimusic industry antistar proscene exhortationsOne the important philosophies the hardcore scene authenticity The pejorative term poseur applied those who associate with punk and adopt its stylistic attributes but are deemed not share understand the underlying values and philosophy Joe Keithley the vocalist DOA said interview For every person sporting anarchy symbol without understanding theres older punk who thinks theyre poseur the vein earlier punk rock most hardcore punk bands have followed the traditional singerguitarbassdrum format The songwriting has more emphasis rhythm rather than melody Critic Steven Blush writes The Sex Pistols were still rocknrolllike the craziest version Chuck Berry Hardcore was radical departure from that wasnt versechorus rock dispelled any notion what songwriting supposed Its its own form According AllMusic the overall blueprint for hardcore was playing louder harder and faster Hardcore was reaction the cosmopolitan artschool style new wave music Hardcore eschewed nuance technique and the avantgarde and instead emphasized speed and rhythmic intensity using unpredictable song forms and abrupt tempo changes The impact powerful volume important hardcore Noisey magazine describes one hardcore band allencompassing fullvolume assault which every instrument sounds like its competing for the most power and highest volume Scott Wilson states that the hardcore the Bad Brains emphasized two elements offthecharts loudness which reached level threatening powerful uncompromising noise and rhythm place the typically focusedon elements mainstream rock music harmony and pitch melody Hardcore vocalists often shout scream chant along with the music using vocal intensity and abrasive tone The shouting hardcore vocalists often accompanied audience members who are singing along making the hardcore vocalist like the leader mob Steven Blush describes one early Minor Threat show where the crowd was singing the lyrics loud they could heard over the system Hardcore vocal lines are often based minor scales and songs may include shouted background vocals from the other band members Hardcore lyrics expressed the frustration and political disillusionment youth who were against 1980sera affluence consumerism greed Reagan politics and authority The polarizing sociopolitical messages hardcore lyrics and outrageous onstage behaviour meant that the genre garnered mainstream popularity hardcore guitarists frequently play fast power chords with heavily distorted and amplified tone creating what has been called buzzsaw sound Guitar parts can sometimes complex technically versatile and rhythmically challenging Hardcore guitarists use some approaches that are similar their thrash counterparts very high output pickups lots upper midrange full bassheavy tone and the use both guitar amp distortion and Tube Screamer similar overdrive pedal but without speaker distortion Guitar melody lines usually use the same minor scales used vocalists although some solos use pentatonic scales Hardcore guitarists sometimes play solos octave leads and grooves well tapping into the various feedback and harmonic noises available them There are generally fewer guitar solos hardcore than mainstream rock because solos were viewed representing the excess and superficiality mainstream commercial rock Hardcore bassists use varied rhythms their basslines ranging from longer held notes whole notes and half notes quarter notes rapid eighth note sixteenth note runs play rapid bass lines that would hard play with the fingers some bassists use pick Some bassists play fuzz bass overdriving their bass tone Hardcore drumming with the drummer hitting the drums hard has been called the engine and most essential element the genres aggressive sound unrelenting anger Two other key elements for hardcore drummers are playing tight with the other musicians especially the bassist this does not mean metronomic time indeed coordinated tempo shifts are used many important hardcore albums and the drummer should have listened lot hardcore that she can understand the raw emotions expresses Lucky Lehrer the drummer and cofounder the Circle Jerks 1979 was early developer hardcore drumming has been called the Godfather hardcore drumming and Flipside zine calls him the best punk drummer According Tobias Hurwitz hardcore drumming falls somewhere between the straightahead rock styles oldschool punk and the frantic warpspeed bashing thrash Some hardcore punk drummers play fast beat one moment and then drop tempo into elaborate musical breakdowns the next Drummers typically play eighth notes the cymbals because the tempos used hardcore would difficult play smaller subdivision the beat Hardcore punk lyrics often express antiestablishment antimilitarist antiauthoritarian antiviolence and proenvironmentalist sentiments addition other typically leftwing anarchist egalitarian political views During the 1980s the subculture often rejected what was perceived yuppie materialism and interventionist American foreign policy Numerous hardcore punk bands have taken far left political stances such anarchism other varieties socialism and the 1980s expressed opposition political leaders such then president Ronald Reagan and British prime minister Margaret Thatcher Reagans economic policies sometimes dubbed Reaganomics and social conservatism were common subjects for criticism hardcore bands the time Jimmy Gestapo Murphys Law however endorsed Reagan and even went far call then formerpresident Jimmy Carter pussy 1986 New York Magazine cover story Shortly after Reagans death 2004 the Maximumrocknroll radio show aired episode composed antiReagan songs early hardcore punk bands Certain hardcore punk bands have conveyed messages sometimes deemed politically incorrect placing offensive content their lyrics and relying stage antics shock listeners and people their audience Boston band the FUs generated controversy with their 1983 album America whose lyrics contained what appeared conservative and patriotic views Its messages were sometimes taken literally when they were actually intended parody conservative bands Another act from Massachusetts Vile were known insult women minorities and homosexuals their lyrics and would even far putting their albums the windshields peoples cars the other hand Tim Yohannan and the influential punk rock fanzine Maximumrocknroll were criticized some punks for acting the politically correct scene police and having what was perceived very narrow definition what fits into Punk and apparently being authoritarian and trying dominate the scene with their views During the 20012009 United States presidency George Bush was not uncommon for hardcore bands express antiBush messages During the 2004 United States pre